      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "# Cost of Living vs Purchasing Power & Quality of Life  \n",
        "### Cross-Country Data Analysis\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "## Overview\n",
        "\n",
        "This notebook presents a structured, data-driven examination of the relationship between **cost of living**, **purchasing power**, and **quality of life** across countries.  \n",
        "The goal is not to rank countries or draw policy prescriptions, but to map cross-country patterns, dispersion, and structural differences in how living standards are achieved.\n",
        "\n",
        "The analysis is exploratory and comparative in nature, emphasizing methodological rigor, transparency, and interpretability.\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "## Research Motivation\n",
        "\n",
        "Cross-country comparisons of living standards are often reduced to headline rankings or single composite scores. While useful at a high level, such approaches tend to obscure:\n",
        "\n",
        "- Heterogeneity within high–quality-of-life countries  \n",
        "- Structural differences between high-cost and low-cost models  \n",
        "- Outliers that do not conform to average relationships  \n",
        "\n",
        "This project is motivated by the question of whether high quality of life necessarily requires high living costs, or whether alternative, more cost-efficient national models exist.\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "## Data Structure and Unit of Analysis\n",
        "\n",
        "The original dataset contains multiple observations per country across different years. Treating these observations independently would overweight countries with more time coverage and violate the assumption of equal contribution across units.\n",
        "\n",
        "To ensure fair cross-country comparison, the analysis aggregates the data to the **country level** by computing multi-year averages for each index. This transforms the dataset into a cross-sectional country-level structure, where each country is represented once.\n",
        "\n",
        "This design choice shifts the focus from short-term fluctuations to long-run, structural differences between countries.\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "## Core Variables\n",
        "\n",
        "The analysis centers on three composite indices:\n",
        "\n",
        "- **Cost of Living Index** — a relative measure of price levels  \n",
        "- **Purchasing Power Index** — a relative measure of income and affordability  \n",
        "- **Quality of Life Index** — a multidimensional indicator of overall living standards  \n",
        "\n",
        "All variables are index-based rather than measured in natural units, which implies that the analysis focuses on relative relationships and comparisons rather than absolute levels.\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "## Exploratory Analysis\n",
        "\n",
        "The initial exploratory phase examines the relationship between cost of living and purchasing power across countries. While a strong positive association is observed, the data also exhibit substantial dispersion, indicating that similar price levels can coexist with very different levels of purchasing power.\n",
        "\n",
        "This dispersion motivates a deeper structural analysis rather than reliance on simple correlations or averages.\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "## Analytical Framework: Cost–Purchasing Power Quadrants\n",
        "\n",
        "To interpret cross-country differences more clearly, countries are classified using a quadrant-based framework defined by their position relative to the global mean of:\n",
        "\n",
        "- Cost of living  \n",
        "- Purchasing power  \n",
        "\n",
        "This framework yields four conceptual categories:\n",
        "\n",
        "- High cost / Low purchasing power  \n",
        "- Low cost / High purchasing power  \n",
        "- High cost / High purchasing power  \n",
        "- Low cost / Low purchasing power  \n",
        "\n",
        "The quadrant model is used as a heuristic tool to highlight structural patterns and inefficiencies, not as a ranking mechanism.\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "## Distributional Perspective\n",
        "\n",
        "Rather than relying on mean comparisons alone, the analysis examines how cost of living is distributed within quality-of-life tiers. Countries are grouped into quantiles based on their quality-of-life index, and the dispersion of living costs within each group is analyzed.\n",
        "\n",
        "This distributional approach reveals that even among high–quality-of-life countries, living costs vary widely. High living standards are therefore not associated with a single cost structure, but with a range of economic configurations.\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "## Cost–Quality Efficiency Lens\n",
        "\n",
        "To further explore this heterogeneity, the analysis introduces a simple efficiency metric defined as the ratio of quality of life to cost of living. This metric serves as a comparative lens for identifying countries that achieve relatively high living standards without extreme price levels.\n",
        "\n",
        "The efficiency measure is descriptive and illustrative. It is not intended as a normative ranking or policy recommendation, but as a way to highlight alternative structural models of well-being.\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "## Country-Level Aggregation and Comparison\n",
        "\n",
        "After aggregating the data at the country level, the analysis revisits the distribution of quality of life and cost of living. Countries are compared within high–quality-of-life groups to distinguish between relatively lower-cost and higher-cost models that achieve similar outcomes.\n",
        "\n",
        "This step reinforces the idea that quality of life can be produced through multiple structural paths.\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "## Statistical Appendix: Descriptive Robustness Check\n",
        "\n",
        "As a robustness check, the notebook includes descriptive linear regression analysis using the country-level aggregated dataset.\n",
        "\n",
        "Two models are estimated:\n",
        "\n",
        "- A baseline model relating quality of life to cost of living  \n",
        "- An extended model including both cost of living and purchasing power  \n",
        "\n",
        "The results show that while cost of living is positively associated with quality of life in isolation, this relationship loses statistical significance once purchasing power is included. Purchasing power emerges as the dominant correlate of quality of life.\n",
        "\n",
        "Robust standard errors and basic diagnostic checks are reported to ensure that the findings are not driven by heteroskedasticity or multicollinearity. These regressions are interpreted strictly as descriptive associations, not causal relationships.\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "## Key Takeaways\n",
        "\n",
        "- Cost of living alone does not determine quality of life  \n",
        "- Higher quality of life is associated with higher costs on average, but with substantial dispersion  \n",
        "- Purchasing power plays a central role in explaining quality-of-life differences  \n",
        "- Multiple structural models can deliver high living standards, including relatively cost-efficient ones  \n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "## Scope and Limitations\n",
        "\n",
        "This analysis is explicitly non-causal and index-based. The results should be interpreted as descriptive evidence intended to map patterns and generate insight, rather than to identify causal mechanisms or policy prescriptions.\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "## Conclusion\n",
        "\n",
        "This project provides a structured, comparative mapping of how countries differ in the relationship between prices, income, and quality of life. By moving beyond averages and rankings, it highlights the diversity of national models and demonstrates that high living standards can coexist with very different cost structures.\n",
        "\n",
        "The framework and findings are intended as a foundation for further research, refinement, and theoretical interpretation rather than as definitive conclusions.\n"
      ],

      }

        "## Analytical Framework: Cost–Power Quadrant Model\n",
        "\n",
        "To better interpret cross-country differences, countries were classified into four analytical quadrants based on their relative position to the global mean:\n",
        "\n",
        "1. High Cost of Living & Low Purchasing Power (\"Expensive–Weak\")\n",
        "2. Low Cost of Living & High Purchasing Power (\"Cheap–Strong\")\n",
        "3. High Cost of Living & High Purchasing Power (\"Expensive–Strong\")\n",
        "4. Low Cost of Living & Low Purchasing Power (\"Cheap–Weak\")\n",
        "\n",
        "This framework enables identifying structural inefficiencies, affordability advantages, and premium living models across countries.\n"
      ],

      }

        "\n",
        "expensive_weak[['Country', 'Cost of Living Index', 'Purchasing Power Index']] \\\n",
        "    .sort_values('Cost of Living Index', ascending=False) \\\n",

            "text/plain": [
              "from matplotlib import pyplot as plt\n",
              "import seaborn as sns\n",
              "def _plot_series(series, series_name, series_index=0):\n",
              "  palette = list(sns.palettes.mpl_palette('Dark2'))\n",
              "  xs = series['index']\n",
              "  ys = series['Quality of Life Index']\n",
              "  \n",
              "  plt.plot(xs, ys, label=series_name, color=palette[series_index % len(palette)])\n",
              "\n",
              "fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(10, 5.2), layout='constrained')\n",
              "df_sorted = _df_4.sort_values('index', ascending=True)\n",
              "for i, (series_name, series) in enumerate(df_sorted.groupby('Country')):\n",
              "  _plot_series(series, series_name, i)\n",
              "  fig.legend(title='Country', bbox_to_anchor=(1, 1), loc='upper left')\n",
              "sns.despine(fig=fig, ax=ax)\n",
              "plt.xlabel('index')\n",
              "_ = plt.ylabel('Quality of Life Index')"

            "text/plain": [
              "from matplotlib import pyplot as plt\n",
              "import seaborn as sns\n",
              "def _plot_series(series, series_name, series_index=0):\n",
              "  palette = list(sns.palettes.mpl_palette('Dark2'))\n",
              "  counted = (series['index']\n",
              "                .value_counts()\n",
              "              .reset_index(name='counts')\n",
              "              .rename({'index': 'index'}, axis=1)\n",
              "              .sort_values('index', ascending=True))\n",
              "  xs = counted['index']\n",
              "  ys = counted['counts']\n",
              "  plt.plot(xs, ys, label=series_name, color=palette[series_index % len(palette)])\n",
              "\n",
              "fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(10, 5.2), layout='constrained')\n",
              "df_sorted = _df_5.sort_values('index', ascending=True)\n",
              "for i, (series_name, series) in enumerate(df_sorted.groupby('Country')):\n",
              "  _plot_series(series, series_name, i)\n",
              "  fig.legend(title='Country', bbox_to_anchor=(1, 1), loc='upper left')\n",
              "sns.despine(fig=fig, ax=ax)\n",
              "plt.xlabel('index')\n",
              "_ = plt.ylabel('count()')"
            ],

    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "### Research Question\n",
        "\n",
        "How does cost of living relate to purchasing power and quality of life across countries,\n",
        "and are there countries that achieve high quality of life without extreme living costs?\n"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "eN4EcvX-s4sd"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "### Key Conclusions\n",
        "\n",
        "• Cost of living alone does not determine quality of life.\n",
        "• Higher quality of life is associated with higher costs on average, but with significant dispersion.\n",
        "• Several countries achieve high quality of life with moderate living costs, indicating structural and social efficiency.\n",
        "• Aggregating data at the country level is essential for fair cross-country comparison.\n"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "2hYsxUVds6r5"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "## Appendix (Optional): Statistical Validation — Descriptive Regression Check\n",
        "\n",
        "### Purpose\n",
        "This appendix provides a **descriptive robustness check** using linear regression to quantify the association between **Cost of Living**, **Purchasing Power**, and **Quality of Life** across countries.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Important Scope Note (Non-Causal)\n",
        "- The dataset is observational and index-based.\n",
        "- The analysis does **not** identify causal effects.\n",
        "- Results should be interpreted as **associations** consistent with the exploratory findings (dispersion, heterogeneity, and multiple high-QoL models).\n",
        "\n",
        "### Unit of Analysis\n",
        "All regressions are estimated on the **country-level aggregated dataset** (one row per country) to avoid temporal duplication from country-year observations.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Models\n",
        "- **Model 1:** QoL ~ Cost of Living  \n",
        "- **Model 2:** QoL ~ Cost of Living + Purchasing Power\n",
        "\n",
        "We report coefficient estimates, p-values, confidence intervals, and model fit metrics, and we include basic diagnostics and robust standard errors.\n"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "PUTE8bunMDDx"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": [

      ],

      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []

        "Appendix Summary: Statistical Robustness Check\n",
        "This appendix adds a descriptive statistical validation layer to the analysis.\n",
        "Using country-level aggregated data, we estimated linear regression models to quantify the association between cost of living, purchasing power, and quality of life.\n",
        "The results confirm that while cost of living shows a positive association with quality of life when examined in isolation, this relationship is not robust once purchasing power is included in the model. Purchasing power emerges as the dominant explanatory variable, while cost of living loses statistical significance.\n",
        "These findings reinforce the core conclusions of the main analysis: quality of life differences across countries are not driven by price levels alone, but by structural efficiency and purchasing power relative to cost. The regression results are interpreted as descriptive associations, not causal effects, and serve as a robustness check rather than a standalone inferential claim."
